Current persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:
No circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.


2026-04-21 01:29:58 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Control module 6'] hypothesis_explanation='Tracing shows the series chain from PSU through all modules has correct polarity, but Control Input Cable (+) 6 has its negative-side port disconnected (floating). Voltage testing with all switches ON found ~12 V present at module 6 input positive relative to PSU negative, but 0 V at module 6 output positive, so module 6 does not pass current to downstream modules. With the negative port open, the switch path and the LED branch in module 6 have no return to 0 V, leaving the module electrically floating and breaking the series path. This explains why all downstream indicators and the load lamp remain off despite good PSU output. The root cause is therefore an internal/open connection fault within Control Module 6 (specifically its negative-side port/switch path), so repairing or replacing Control Module 6 should restore continuity and allow the lamp to operate when all switches are ON.'
