Someone executed a (additional) diagnostic action on the system. The action (type, target_component, description, outcome) was: 
TYPE: Test,
TARGET: Control Input / Output Cables (+) 5, (+) 6, and (+) 7 (fast-connection terminals only),
DESCRIPTION: With power OFF and all modules left in their current physical arrangement, use an ohmmeter/continuity tester to map the actual series path of the +12 V conductor through the three cable segments around module 6. Specifically: (1) Identify the two fast-connection terminals that form the intended positive series path between the output of control module 5 and the input of control module 7, bypassing module 6 entirely, and measure continuity between them; (2) Measure continuity from module 5 positive output terminal to each of the two positive-side terminals of Control Input Cable (+) 6, and from each of the two positive-side terminals of Control Output Cable (+) 6 to module 7 positive input terminal. Record which terminal pairs are electrically common and which are open, to reveal any mis-mated or cross-connected positive plugs that interrupt the 12 V series line even though polarity appears correct visually.,
RESULT: Continuity is good from Control Output Cable (+) 5 to Control Input Cable (+) 6 (short, ~0.1 Ω) and from Control Output Cable (+) 6 to Control Input Cable (+) 7 (short, ~0.1 Ω). There is no direct continuity from Control Output Cable (+) 5 to Control Input Cable (+) 7 (open circuit), indicating the +12 V path goes through the series of Control Input/Output Cables (+) 6 rather than directly bypassing module 6. No POLARITY INVERSION DETECTED in the measured positive-side connections.
Current persistent circuit state [differences with the starting state]:
No circuit-level changes introduced by diagnostics.


